SIMPLE: remise
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Remise
<hw>Re*mise"</hw> <pr>(r?-m?z")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Remised</conjf>
<pr>(-m?zd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Remising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>remise</ets> delivery,
surrender, fr. <ets>remettre</ets> to put back, deliver, L.
<ets>remittere</ets>. See <er>Remit</er>.]</ety> <def>To send, give, or
grant back; to release a claim to; to resign or surrender by deed; to
return.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Remise
<hw>Re*mise"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A giving or
granting back; surrender; return; release, as of a claim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Remise
<hw>Re*mise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A house
for covered carriages; a chaise house.</def>
<rj><au>Sterne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A livery carriage of a kind superior to an ordinary
fiacre; -- so called because kept in a remise.</def>
<rj><au>Cooper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remiss</ent>⟦br⟧
